# koom — production deployment environment variables template
#
# Copy this file to web/.env.prod.local and fill in the blanks. Both
# files live in the `web/` directory; `.env.prod.local` is gitignored
# while this template is committed. The doctor script
# (`npm run doctor`) will auto-create `.env.prod.local` from this
# template the first time it runs.
#
# ── Why a separate file from .env.local? ──
#
# `.env.local` holds values needed for LOCAL DEVELOPMENT. The values
# in this file are only useful for VALIDATING and DEPLOYING TO
# PRODUCTION from your dev machine. Keeping them separate means:
#
#   - `.env.local` only has things that affect the local dev stack.
#     Editing it never risks nudging production values.
#   - The doctor script can validate local-dev readiness and
#     production readiness independently, without asking you to swap
#     values between runs.
#   - A future `npm run vercel:sync` script has a single, unambiguous
#     file to read production-only settings from.
#
# ── What about the production Postgres URL? ──
#
# It does not live here. Production Postgres is derived live from the
# Supabase CLI link. After you create your hosted Supabase project,
# run `npx -y supabase@2.87.2 login` and then:
#
#   npx -y supabase@2.87.2 link --project-ref=<your-project-ref>
#
# That writes the linked project metadata (including a ready-to-use
# pooler connection URL) into `supabase/.temp/`. The doctor reads
# those files directly, uses `SUPABASE_DB_PASSWORD` from
# `.env.local` for authentication, and checks that the remote
# Postgres accepts a connection. No duplication, no drift.


# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Vercel deployment
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Used by the doctor script to validate that your Vercel project is
# reachable and the token has access. A future `npm run vercel:sync`
# script will also use these to push production environment variables
# into the Vercel project from a single command.
#
# Step 1: Deploy the web app to Vercel (manually, for v1).
#         Push the koom repo to GitHub and import it at
#         https://vercel.com/new. Then in the Vercel project
#         settings → Environment Variables, paste the values from
#         `web/.env.local` that apply in production:
#           - SUPABASE_DB_PASSWORD → not needed (only used locally)
#           - DATABASE_URL        → use the hosted Supabase pooler
#                                    URL from your project's dashboard
#                                    (Project Settings → Database →
#                                    Connection string → URI)
#           - R2_BUCKET, R2_ACCOUNT_ID, R2_ACCESS_KEY_ID,
#             R2_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY, R2_PUBLIC_BASE_URL → same values
#           - KOOM_PUBLIC_BASE_URL → your Vercel URL, not localhost
#           - KOOM_ADMIN_SECRET   → same value as local
#
# Step 2: Mint a Vercel token.
#         Go to https://vercel.com/account/tokens and create a token
#         scoped to the account that owns the koom project. Paste it
#         into VERCEL_TOKEN below.
#
# Step 3: Copy the project ID.
#         In the Vercel dashboard, open the koom project → Settings
#         → General → "Project ID" (the `prj_...` string, NOT the
#         project slug). Paste it into VERCEL_PROJECT_ID below.

VERCEL_TOKEN=
VERCEL_PROJECT_ID=
